<DOC><DOCNO> AP890418-0200 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 2011EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-HousingSuit     04-18 0224</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Housing Suit,1st ld-writethru, a0715,220</SECOND><HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS day of week in lead</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The first lawsuit filed under a new lawprohibiting housing discrimination against families with childrenwas filed Tuesday against the owners of a New Jersey apartmentcomplex.   The suit, filed by the Justice Department's civil rightsdivision, charges that LaFonge Associates violated the recentlyamended Fair Housing Act by refusing to rent a one-bedroomapartment to a single parent and a child.   Amendments to the Fair Housing Act that were enacted by Congresslast year housing discrimination against people with handicaps andthose with children. Retirement communities with special facilitiesfor elderly people are exempt from the law.   The suit charged that LaFonge Associates ``engaged in a patternof practice of discrimination against persons on the basis offamilial status in the rental of dwellings .''   The company, which owns Somerset Mews Apartments in FranklinTownship of Somerset County, N.J., was accused of tellingprospective tenants that it preferred to families without children.   The Justice Department, acting on a complaint by the HousingCoalition of Middlesex County of New Brunswick, sought aninjunction to force the company to stop the alleged discriminatorypractices.   The suit, filed in U.S. District Court in New Jersey, also seekscompensatory damages and a civil penalty ``in order to vindicatethe public interest.''</TEXT></DOC>